{"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/mm4\/mm4rigidbody\/setthermalkineticenergy(temperature:heatcapacity:)"]}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"tokens":[{"text":"mutating","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"keyword","text":"func"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"setThermalKineticEnergy"},{"kind":"text","text":"("},{"text":"temperature","kind":"externalParam"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"preciseIdentifier":"s:Sf","text":"Float","kind":"typeIdentifier"},{"text":", ","kind":"text"},{"text":"heatCapacity","kind":"externalParam"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"preciseIdentifier":"s:Sf","kind":"typeIdentifier","text":"Float"},{"kind":"text","text":" = 1.5)"}],"platforms":["macOS"],"languages":["swift"]}]},{"parameters":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The temperature to match the thermal energy to,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"in kelvin."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"name":"temperature"},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The partitioning of overall thermal energy in"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"thermodynamic units per atom (kT or R). The default value is 1.5."}]}],"name":"heatCapacity"}],"kind":"parameters"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Discussion","anchor":"discussion"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Some of the energy will be lost to thermal potential energy during a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"simulation. This information can technically be recovered from the atoms’"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"positions. Typical use cases minimize the system at 0 K, then initialize"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the simulator at room temperature. It is not anticipated that users will","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"extract temperature (e.g. local temperature differentials) from the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"simulation."}]},{"type":"aside","style":"warning","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"There is no trivial method to translate between thermal energy"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and temperature. Therefore, you must find a heat capacity lookup table"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"from an external source. Diamond has"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/physics.stackexchange.com\/a\/583043","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" heat","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"capacity characteristics than other solids. In 1957, C. V. Raman devised a","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"http:\/\/dspace.rri.res.in\/bitstream\/2289\/1763\/1\/1957%20Proc%20Indian%20Acad%20Sci%20A%20V46%20p323-332.pdf"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to map temperature to heat capacity for diamond. Experimental measurements"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"matched the prediction with around 1% margin of error.","type":"text"}]}],"name":"Warning"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Heat capacity in kT\/atom equals the value in J\/mol-K divided by 8.314. For","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"reference, here are some common heat capacities:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"By the equipartition theorem, ideal gases are 1.5 kT."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Most crystalline solids approach 3.0 kT at high temperatures.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Diamond: 0.74 kT at 298 K, 1.62 kT at 500 K ("},{"type":"reference","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Raman, 1957"}],"isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Raman, 1957","identifier":"http:\/\/dspace.rri.res.in\/bitstream\/2289\/1763\/1\/1957%20Proc%20Indian%20Acad%20Sci%20A%20V46%20p323-332.pdf"},{"type":"text","text":")."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Moissanite: 1.62 kT at 298 K, 2.31 kT at 500 K ("},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1016\/S0021-9614(71)80045-9"},{"type":"text","text":")."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Silicon: 2.41 kT at 298 K, 2.84 kT at 500 K ("},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/srd.nist.gov\/JPCRD\/jpcrd298.pdf","isActive":true},{"text":").","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"MaterialHeatCapacities"}]}]}],"sections":[],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Set the thermal kinetic energy to match a given temperature, assuming"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"positions are energy-minimized at 0 K."}],"metadata":{"title":"setThermalKineticEnergy(temperature:heatCapacity:)","role":"symbol","externalID":"s:3MM40A9RigidBodyV23setThermalKineticEnergy11temperature12heatCapacityySf_SftF","extendedModule":"MM4","roleHeading":"Instance Method","modules":[{"name":"MM4"}],"symbolKind":"method","fragments":[{"text":"func","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"setThermalKineticEnergy","kind":"identifier"},{"kind":"text","text":"("},{"text":"temperature","kind":"externalParam"},{"kind":"text","text":": "},{"text":"Float","kind":"typeIdentifier","preciseIdentifier":"s:Sf"},{"text":", ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"externalParam","text":"heatCapacity"},{"kind":"text","text":": "},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","text":"Float","preciseIdentifier":"s:Sf"},{"kind":"text","text":")"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4RigidBody"]]},"kind":"symbol","schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"identifier